{{2022 Winter Olympics}}

The [[2022 Winter Olympics]], officially known as the XXIV Olympic Winter Games, were a winter multi-sport event held in [[Beijing]], China, from 4 to 20 February. A total of 2,871 athletes from 91 nations participated in 109 events in seven sports across 15 disciplines.

Overall 29 nations received at least one medal, and 23 of them won at least one gold medal. Athletes from [[Norway at the 2022 Winter Olympics|Norway]] won the most medals overall, with 37, and the most gold medals, with 16. The latter record was the highest gold medal tally at a single Winter Games. Host nation [[China at the 2022 Winter Olympics|China]] won nine gold medals surpassing its gold medal tally of five during the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 winter edition]]. Athletes from that nation also won 15 medals overall, which eclipsed its record of 11 at both the [[2006 Winter Olympics|2006]] and 2010 winter editions.

Biathletes [[Johannes Thingnes Bø]], [[Quentin Fillon Maillet]], and [[Marte Olsbu Røiseland]], and cross-country skier [[Alexander Bolshunov]] won the most total medals at the games with five each. Bø also earned the most gold medals with four. Snowboarder [[Zoi Sadowski-Synnott]] of [[New Zealand at the 2022 Winter Olympics|New Zealand]] won the first Winter Olympic gold medal for that nation. [[Germany at the 2022 Winter Olympics|Germany]] achieved a podium sweep in the [[Bobsleigh at the 2022 Winter Olympics – Two-man|men's two-man bobsleigh competition]] with [[Francesco Friedrich]] and [[Thorsten Margis]]	winning gold, [[Johannes Lochner]] and [[Florian Bauer]] earning silver, and [[Christoph Hafer]] and [[Matthias Sommer]] attaining bronze.

